#              1. ALL JSON SCHEMA DRAFTS — implements:
#                   * Draft 4 (2013)
#                   * Draft 6 (2017)
#                   * Draft 7 (2019)
#                   * Draft 2019-09
#                   * Draft 2020-12
#                   * JSON Type Definition (RFC 8927)
#                 The ONLY validator across all three languages
#                 in this taxonomy that supports JTD (JSON Type
#                 Definition) — a JSON Schema alternative
#                 standardized by RFC 8927 in 2020.
#              2. CODE-GENERATION COMPILATION — ajv compiles
#                 schemas into JavaScript FUNCTIONS at runtime
#                 (not just optimized data structures).  The
#                 compiled validator is a generated function
#                 that runs at native JIT speed:
#                   import Ajv from 'ajv';
#                   const ajv = new Ajv();
#                   const validate = ajv.compile(schema);
#                   // validate is now a generated JS function
#                   const valid = validate(data);
#                   if (!valid) console.log(validate.errors);
#                 ~10x faster than typical interpretive
#                 validators.  Distinct from Stranger6667/
#                 jsonschema (compiled validation graph but
#                 not JIT-emitted) and santhosh-tekuri/
#                 jsonschema (compiled graph, no JIT).
#              3. FASTEST JSON SCHEMA VALIDATOR ACROSS ALL
#                 LANGUAGES — ajv benchmarks consistently
#                 ahead of validators in Python (jsonschema-
#                 rs), Go (santhosh-tekuri), Rust
#                 (Stranger6667/jsonschema), Java (everit-
#                 org/json-schema), C# (Newtonsoft.Json.Schema).
#                 Code-gen approach is the secret sauce.
#              4. STANDALONE VALIDATION CODE GENERATION —
#                 `ajv compile-schema schema.json
#                 -o validators.js` (via ajv-cli) emits
#                 standalone JS files containing only the
#                 generated validators (no ajv runtime needed
#                 at deployment).  Used in environments where
#                 bundle size matters (browser, AWS Lambda).
#              5. PLUGIN ECOSYSTEM — ajv-formats (RFC 3339
#                 date-time, email, uri, etc.), ajv-keywords
#                 (custom keywords: typeof / instanceof /
#                 transform), ajv-errors (custom error
#                 messages), ajv-i18n (internationalized
#                 errors), ajv-bsontype (BSON type
#                 validation), ajv-merge-patch (JSON Merge
#                 Patch + JSON Patch).
#              6. STRICT MODE — `new Ajv({ strict: true })`
#                 catches schema errors early (unknown
#                 keywords, mistakes in references, etc.);
#                 default since ajv v7.  Helps avoid bugs in
#                 schema development.
#              7. DISCRIMINATOR KEYWORD — implements the
#                 OpenAPI 3.0+ `discriminator` keyword for
#                 polymorphic schemas (useful for OpenAPI/
#                 Swagger validation).  Distinct from
#                 Stranger6667/jsonschema (also supports) and
#                 santhosh-tekuri/jsonschema (also supports).
#              8. ASYNC VALIDATION — `new Ajv({ async: true })`
#                 enables Promise-returning validators for
#                 async format/keyword validators (e.g.,
#                 database-lookup constraints).
#              9. JSON TYPE DEFINITION (JTD) MODE — `new
#                 Ajv({ jtd: true })` switches to JTD mode
#                 (RFC 8927).  JTD is a simpler alternative
#                 to JSON Schema designed for type-driven
#                 code-generation.  ajv is the canonical
#                 reference implementation.
#             10. EVGENY-POBEREZKIN / ajv-validator
